<!-- Identifier below is the NIC's MAC address, not the interface alias
     ("Ethernet") this used to match on. A real deployment on real
     hardware ended up with this component silently never applied at all:
     Setup didn't error, the adapter simply stayed on its DHCP default,
     exactly what Microsoft's own component reference warns alias/LUID
     matching is prone to ("the LUID and interface aliases for each
     interface are not guaranteed to be the same between different
     builds"). MAC address is the deterministic alternative the same
     reference documents Identifier as accepting, and DeployCore already
     controls it: hypervisors/defaults.py's generate_mac_address()
     assigns it explicitly to the VM's NIC at creation time (rather than
     letting the hypervisor auto-generate one), before this file is ever
     rendered, so the exact same value that's actually on the NIC is what
     gets matched here - no enumeration-order guesswork left at all.

     Configured here, in the specialize pass, rather than over WinRM in
     post_install: that used to connect to whatever DHCP handed out
     first, then reconfigure to the static address remotely, which can't
     work at all on a network with no DHCP server to hand out that first
     address in the first place. This way the static config is live
     before Windows Setup even finishes, no DHCP involved anywhere.

     Element order below is load-bearing, not stylistic: Microsoft's own
     schema requires Interface's children in the exact order Ipv4Settings,
     Identifier, UnicastIpAddresses, Routes (confirmed against
     learn.microsoft.com's own component reference, which explicitly warns
     about this), and Route's children in the exact order Identifier,
     Metric, NextHopAddress, Prefix. Getting either wrong doesn't raise a
     helpful XML error, Setup just fails specialize-pass processing with a
     generic "Windows installieren: Die Installation konnte nicht
     abgeschlossen werden" dialog and no other detail, exactly what an
     earlier version of this file did (Identifier before Ipv4Settings,
     Route fields in the wrong order) before being fixed against a real,
     working example (cloudfoundry-community/windows-stemcell-concourse's
     autounattend.xml) and Microsoft's own documented ordering. -->
<component name="Microsoft-Windows-TCPIP" processorArchitecture="amd64" publicKeyToken="31bf3856ad364e35" language="neutral" versionScope="nonSxS" xmlns:wcm="http://schemas.microsoft.com/WMIConfig/2002/State">
    <Interfaces>
        <Interface wcm:action="add">
            <Ipv4Settings>
                <DhcpEnabled>false</DhcpEnabled>
            </Ipv4Settings>
            <Identifier>{{ mac_address_dashes }}</Identifier>
            <UnicastIpAddresses>
                <IpAddress wcm:action="add" wcm:keyValue="1">{{ deployment.static_ip }}/{{ static_prefix }}</IpAddress>
            </UnicastIpAddresses>
{% if deployment.static_gateway %}
            <Routes>
                <Route wcm:action="add">
                    <Identifier>1</Identifier>
                    <Metric>1</Metric>
                    <NextHopAddress>{{ deployment.static_gateway }}</NextHopAddress>
                    <Prefix>0.0.0.0/0</Prefix>
                </Route>
            </Routes>
{% endif %}
        </Interface>
    </Interfaces>
</component>
{% if deployment.static_dns %}
<component name="Microsoft-Windows-DNS-Client" processorArchitecture="amd64" publicKeyToken="31bf3856ad364e35" language="neutral" versionScope="nonSxS" xmlns:wcm="http://schemas.microsoft.com/WMIConfig/2002/State">
    <Interfaces>
        <Interface wcm:action="add">
            <Identifier>{{ mac_address_dashes }}</Identifier>
            <DNSServerSearchOrder>
{% for dns in deployment.static_dns %}
                <IpAddress wcm:action="add" wcm:keyValue="{{ loop.index }}">{{ dns }}</IpAddress>
{% endfor %}
            </DNSServerSearchOrder>
        </Interface>
    </Interfaces>
</component>
{% endif %}
